            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>
                We moved off the farm in 1965. We had been thinking of making a change in our lives for some time. Ken’s health was beginning to show evidence of a needed slowdown in stress to his physical body and farm work definitely requires much hard work, long hours and complete dedication to the work. Ken has always had those qualities and his success in providing for his family has always been his prime concern. When his health began to decline because of the hard work on the farm, we began to look for some other way of providing for the needs of our family. <br /><br />

                We looked into the possibility of acquiring a franchise for an Arctic Circle drive-in and when one became available in Rexburg we really began to do some very serious thinking. We made the move in 1965. We found a home that we could purchase on Maple Drive in Rexburg and moved in that September. The home was a split-level with four bedrooms, three upstairs and one in the lower level. There was an unfinished family room with an area for laundry, with a kitchen and living room on the main floor. It was a comer lot with a vacant field to the east. There was a good-sized backyard which we later fenced in for privacy. <br /><br />

                We were comfortable there and the change was pretty dramatic considering where we previously lived for 16 years. Mike entered Madison High School as a junior, Marlon as a sophomore, Robert in the 7th grade, Debra 5th and Randy in the 3rd, having missed some school because of needed orthodontic surgery in Boise that fall. Janet started in the first grade. We had good neighbors. The Harts were the next house to the west, Ellises across the street north, Huskinsons behind us on the south next to Walkers. Maple Drive was a friendly street; it ran a little uphill going east and was near the Madison Memorial Hospital. We enjoyed about four years there. <br /><br />

                On Maple Drive, we also became acquainted with the Stokes, Theron and Lola, who became our dear friends, and the Hinckleys and the Wasdens—many wonderful memories of wonderful friends. We lived in the bounds of the Rexburg 4th Ward, the ward from which Mike left to serve his mission. A year or so after acquiring the drive-in, I had the opportunity to take the position of Public Health Nurse for all of Madison County plus two school districts. The position became available when Esther Choales retired. I felt that I needed to return in some capacity to my nursing profession so applied for the job and was accepted. I began work in the office that was located in the Madison County courthouse, up a good flight of marble stairs to the second floor and toward the back of the building. There were two rooms to the office and a secretary worked there as well. <br /><br />

                Mary Gibson became my dear friend through the years that we worked together, 12 in all. I had the responsibility for the whole county and a caseload that required much home visiting and teaching in the school districts to groups of students regarding various health subjects. These were mostly grade and junior high students. During the years in the health department as I worked with other public health nurses in the area, we instigated and conducted various clinics and child care classes in conjunction with Madison Memorial Hospital. I worked with Jerry Daniels, who worked in the Fremont County office and later Janice McNee, who became a dear friend and we established several clinics, such as blood pressure monitoring and mother and baby care classes. We conducted immunization clinics for both counties and worked together to do this. We had immunization clinics for measles, mumps, and rubella, polio, and influenza. <br /><br />

                After several years we were privileged to have a new office built next to the courthouse and it was beautiful. The sanitarian for the county also had his office in the same building. We were happy there and it was an efficient and productive place to work. But it was short-lived because when the Teton Dam broke and the new little office was inundated, we of course had to find another place for the office and ended up in the house that was next to the drive-in down on Main Street. The house was acceptable and big enough and with the bedrooms adjusted to be used for clinic rooms, we were quite comfortable there for a year or two. Later our offices were established in the old hospital building, after the new hospital was built just to the south of the old building. <br /><br />

                Mary Gibson was my faithful secretary, teacher, and friend for all those years. She lived down the hill a block and up another half block with her husband, Garr. Wonderful friends. She taught me much about the office and the needs of the people in Madison County and what my responsibility was to become. I will always treasure her friendship those years. She died while we were serving in the England mission. <br /><br />

                Back to the drive-in. Each of the kids worked in the drive-in as they became of age to do so. They earned money there and also acquired quite a taste for hamburgers, seeing as how they were totally free…well, almost—they did have to work there! We also were a great source of income for Ricks College students; we hired them mostly and provided employment for many of them through those years. When we started the business, hamburgers were selling for 19 cents! And they were good hamburgers! <br /><br />

                The move to Rexburg was especially good for our children. Rexburg, we felt, would be a good place to raise our children. The boys became active in the various sports programs in the schools, especially basketball. Mike was on the varsity team his senior year and Marlon tried out and also made the team but didn’t continue. He found out he was a little too short compared to the other guys, and would not play much so he decided not to continue. Robert did make the varsity football team and basketball team and had a couple of excellent years with the Madison High School teams. We enjoyed many basketball games when our boys were involved and always felt that “community games with local boys playing is where the real sport is.” We enjoyed several years being involved in those sports! <br /><br />

                Debra became involved in the drill team at the high school. Randy sang with the high school choir and Janet was the only girl on the Adams Grade School baseball team! “The kids were good students, had lots of friends who were good kids as well, which we feel contributed to few real problems while they were growing up. Good friends make such a big difference. <br /><br />

                As Ken and I looked back later, we decided that we enjoyed the Rexburg years most—the kids were in their teens and we had lots of fun together. We enjoyed each one and treasure the memories of those years. They were the best!<br /><br />

                Mike received his mission call to New Zealand while we were living on Maple Drive. It was a year that wards could only have two missionaries leave because of the Vietnam War and only few were allowed to be called. There was no farewell in the ward but we had a family get together to see him off. Marion left for his mission to Indonesia when we lived in the new house on Reed Street as well as Robert when he was called to Australia. Randy saved in the Oakland Mission and we worried more about him being in the wicked San Francisco area more than we did the three brothers who were 8,000 miles from home! Debra was called to serve in the Italy Rome Mission and Janet to the Peru Lima Mission. Janet’s call was interesting because when Bishop Parkinson called us serve a mission, Janet was in school at BYU and she was shocked that we would be called to serve a mission when she was not yet married and still attached to her parents, so to speak. <br /><br />

                A wise Bishop Parkinson called her to serve as well when she came home for the weekend and there we were, parents and daughter to serve together! Many blessings! After four years of living in the split level house on Maple Drive we decided to build a new home and chose a lot just down the street and north of the old hospital building, on Reed Street: 431 Reed Street. It was a new neighborhood and few homes had been built yet. We build a home that had three bedrooms upstairs with living room and kitchen-dining area and a downstairs completely finished as well with three bedrooms down there and a huge family room and walk out into the back yard. We build a balcony off to the north from the dining area. <br /><br />

                It was a beautiful home and we loved it. Our neighbors there were the Boyles, who were already in the neighborhood, and the Huskinsons and the Eriksons who built after we did. Also the Carters and the Garners, Strobles, and later on further up the hill the Flamms and our bishop of the 8th Ward at that time, Bishop Jeppesen. We had good neighbors and a quiet, friendly street. My memories of Reed Street and happy memories. I remember Brother Huskinson telling me one time that he used to love to sit by his front window and watch all the activity going on over at the Ken Bird house, always seemed to be happy times and they were.
            </span>

