                The Arctic Circle drive-in that we purchased a franchise for was our main source of income for the first few years we lived in Rexburg. It was built on Main Street and was only the second drive-in in Rexburg at that time. The R &amp; B was the other and had been established in Rexburg for a number of years. This venture was an entirely new one for us and our lifestyle in Rexburg became very different from the farm. Our children loved the change and soon became the best for them. All the kids had duties at the drive-in and soon learned the arts and requirements of serving the public in this manner. We had a thriving business and all enjoyed the lifestyle change. Not many months after we acquired the drive-in, I had the opportunity to accept the County Nurses office and did so, leaving the managing of our new business venture in the hands of my husband and the older teenagers. They did very well and earned their own money this way…as well as developing a love of hamburgers, french fries and milk shakes!<br /><br />
 
                To this day, they have their own tales to tell about their times in the Arctic Circle. It was a very handy place to have lunch during the break at school! We also provided employment for many, many Ricks College students during those years. I remember many of their faces but their names have escaped me—Joy Christensen I remember very well. She managed for us for a year or so if I remember correctly.
            </span>

