            When the property next door to the drive-in, on the east, became available to us, we purchased it and built the Norsemen Apartments for male students at the college. It was a three-story building, the first being a walk out basement. It was one of the first of new student housing apartments in Rexburg at that time, and we had no problem filling with students. There was a stone house on the property, which we were able to rent, with a basement as well, which we rented. <br /><br />

            During the devastation of the Teton Dam breaking, we had mud and water in the bottom floors of the Norsemen as well as in the basement of the house. The drive-in also was almost devastated with about five feet of water throughout. That was in 1976. In 1977 or 78, we sold the franchise for the drive-in and with the government check given to us because of our losses we purchased some property up next to the college and eventually built Riviera I, followed a few years later with Riviera II, and also an older building which became Riviera III. These have been our major sources of income and have provided for us a very comfortable living. 
