                    In 1983, Ken and I returned from the Guatemala City Mission. While we were gone our four sons built a home for us in the Labelle area of Rigby. The property consisted of seven acres,wooded and surrounded by cottonwood trees. We had the plans for the home before we were called to that mission and left thinking we would build when we returned. <br /><br />

                    Our sons were all involved in their own business of Early Bird Sprinkling and Landscaping so were not too busy with any work during the off seasons, so, they got the blueprints for the home and went to work building it for us while we were gone. When we returned, we found the home standing there in the huge field and all framed up and looking great. It seemed so big! And much to our surprise, and not in the plans, there stood a huge shop building in the back and to the east of the home and matching the home! We were amazed and pleased. The home was not finished inside, just framed up so we began to do the work and pleasure of finishing it for the next few months and were able to move in 1984. <br /><br />

                    The boys did the landscaping and so professional! An example of their expertise in their business. There was as planned a two-acre area set aside for pasture so Ken could have some cattle to fatten during the summer months and from then on we always had five or six head of young cattle to be fattened and then sold in the fall. Ken loved this. He spent all of his growing-up years on a farm and because “you can take the boy away from the farm but you can't take the farm away from the boy,” so after 16 years of being away he was so happy to have a few acres to care for with the animals. He also took over the two acres of woods to irrigate and make it into a great place to wander through. <br /><br />

                    We loved being back in the country atmosphere and especially enjoyed that location because we were also neighbors to Marlon and Robert who had built homes down the street on adjoining acres. Our cup of blessings seemed so full and wonderful to have them as neighbors and to have grandchildren so nearby! At this writing, I have lived in LaBelle for 31 years. They have been extremely happy years. Ken passed away in 2003 but I chose to remain in our home. Our children and grandchildren have come to love this home and area as I do and we have had numerous family gatherings here to enjoy and love being together. <br /><br />

                    There are many happy memories of family Sunday dinners with a rousing game of croquet afterward, and family floating the dry bed—we baptized two of our grandchildren in the dry bed! Several family reunions have been held here at home and have become traditional happy family memories. The big arch swing that Randy put up in the big cottonwood tree has become a great memory for all of our grandchildren and is still out there waiting for a grandchild to come and climb in. The squirrels in the back yard and their antics trying to get birdseed from the bird feeder is a favorite view from my kitchen window. <br /><br />

                    Another wonderful blessing the whole family has enjoyed this past eleven years is having at least two horses to graze the pasture during the summer months. Our former bishop's father, Brother Keller, brought his horses to graze during those months and soon became a tradition for summer and one that we have loved for all those years, thus giving me the moniker of “Grandma Horsey” by several grandchildren, a treasured memory now. We decided to sell off the two wooded acres to our neighbor the Bradleys and now once again the woods are a very special and unique place.
