                    From there we went to Indonesia and met many of Marlon’s mission friends as well. They called him “Yellow Bird” down there. We were kind of tickled with that nickname they gave him because of his blond hair. Being there was especially a fun time because we had a very tall Robert, a very rotund Kenneth–he had a little weight on him–and Debra with her long blond hair. That type of person in Indonesia was very, very rare. We attracted a crowd wherever we went. We had people following us and looking at us and wanting to stop and visit. We had a wonderful time. <br /><br />

                    We also went to Taiwan. We went to Thailand. We were in Singapore. We spent time in Japan. We were in Tokyo for three or four days. Then we flew back to Hawaii where Mike and Randy and Janet met us and we spent another week in Hawaii. That was a very special trip and it really gave us the desire to travel as much as we possibly could throughout the following years.  <br /><br />

                    Another special trip we had in our family was when we were going to celebrate our 50th wedding anniversary. Kenneth was just beginning to get into the throes of Alzheimer’s, so we knew that if we wanted to take a family trip together, we must do it at that time. We planned a trip to go to the Mediterranean.  <br /><br />

                    It was kind of interesting how that trip came together, because some of our children just didn’t have the finances to do that trip. They were concerned about it. We wanted to do a family trip for a 50th wedding anniversary, but we didn’t know where we wanted to go or what to do or how long to stay. Finally, Dani called and she said, “Bob is going to put a trip together for us. Let’s go to the Mediterranean. Let’s go take a trip to the Greek Islands.” Oh, my goodness, I thought that would be wonderful. Debra thought it would be wonderful. Bob thought this was wonderful. We began to plan the trip, and pretty soon those who thought they would not go came together, and as a family, all six of our children and their spouses and Ken and I, we made the trip to the Mediterranean.  <br /><br />

                    We went to Rome. We were in Italy for a week or so. We went to the Greek Islands and absolutely fell in love with them. I’ve always wanted to go back to Sorrento in Italy. That was a very special place for me. That was a marvelous trip. The time we spent together as family—we were unbelievably close, helping each other and enjoying the time that we had there. We had some really fun experiences that I would be happy to share with anyone. Anytime they want to listen to me, I’ll tell them of our experiences on that trip.  <br /><br />

                    I’ve been privileged to make several trips to England and travel on the continent with Bob and Janet. They lived there for ten years while Bob was transferred there for his employment. I was privileged to go to England four different times, and it’s become my most favorite place in the world. I love England and I’ll always have special memories. I’m very much connected to England. My ancestors came from there as well, so I guess there’s a spiritual tie there that keeps me in love with England.  <br /><br />

                    It’s interesting, because when Bob and Janet said they’d been transferred to England, I said, “England! Who on earth wants to go and live in England? Are you sure you’re going to do this?” But it just took one trip over there. I went over when Bradley was born. Janet was having some difficulties with that birth, and I went over to help her and just totally fell in love with England.  <br /><br />

                    I’ve been blessed to travel through Europe: Germany, Switzerland, Holland, Italy. I’ve been blessed to travel. I have been blessed to travel! The Lord has been good to me in that respect.  <br /><br />

                    Haven’t been to Alaska. Everyone’s been to Alaska but me.  <br /><br />

                    Oh my goodness, I’ve been to South America. I’ve been to Guatemala. Janet served her mission in Peru and we went down to pick her up and brought her home with us, because we finished our mission in Guatemala as Janet finished hers. We were able to have some of the family go with us, and we went down and picked up Janet and she drove home with us.  <br /><br />

                    Also, when we finished our mission in Guatemala, we brought back with us a fifteen-year-old Guatemalan girl named Norah Alvarado. Her parents were pleased to let her come home with us, and she was able to go to school in Rigby. A couple of years later she came back and attended Ricks College.  <br /><br />

                    I’ve had some beautiful experiences traveling. I’ve had wonderful times and seen a lot of this wonderful world we live in.
